{"title_page": "Tony Vaughan", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tony Vaughan\n| image = \n| fullname = Anthony John Vaughan<ref>{{Hugman|20124|accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1975|10|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Manchester]], England\n| height =\n| position = [[Defender (football)|Defender]]/[[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1=\n| youthclubs1=\n| years1 = 1994\u20131997 | years2 = 1997\u20132000 | years3 = 1999 | years4 = 2000 | years5 = 2000\u20132003 | years6 = 2002 | years7 = 2002 | years8 = 2003 | years9 = 2003\u20132004 | years10 = 2004\u20132006 | years11 =2005| years12 = 2005\u20132006\n| clubs1 = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] | clubs2 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] (loan) | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] (loan) | clubs5 = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] (loan) | clubs7 = \u2192 [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] (loan) | clubs8 = \u2192 [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] (loan) | clubs9 = [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] | clubs10 = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] | clubs11 = \u2192 [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] (loan) | clubs12 =[[Hucknall Town F.C.|Hucknall Town]]\n| caps1 = 65 | goals1 = 3 | caps2 = 59 | goals2 = 2 | caps3 = 14 | goals3 = 0 | caps4 = 6 | goals4 = 0 | caps5 = 37 | goals5 = 1 | caps6 = 5 | goals6 = 0 | caps7 = 4 | goals7 = 0 | caps8 = 12 | goals8 = 1 | caps9 = 32 | goals9 = 2 | caps10 = 27 | goals10 = 4 | caps11 = 10 | goals11 = 1| caps12 = | goals12 =\n| nationalyears1=\n| nationalteam1=\n| nationalcaps1= | nationalgoals1 =\n| club-update =\n| ntupdate =\n}}\n'''Anthony John Vaughan''' (born 11 October 1975 in [[Manchester]]) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[defender (football)|defender]]/[[midfielder]] from 1994 until 2006.\n\nHe played [[Premier League]] football for [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] before moving into the [[Football League]] with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]], [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]], [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] and [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]]. He also played in the [[Scottish Premier League]] for [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] and finished his career in non-league football with [[Hucknall Town F.C.|Hucknall Town]].\n\n==Playing career==\nVaughan was a product of the [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] youth scheme where he became a trainee.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/manchester_city/article5780357.ece Manchester City save best till last]</ref> He later joined [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich]] as a youth, before making his full debut on 23 October 1994 against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at Stamford Bridge in the [[FA Premier League]]. He started 10 times in that season where Ipswich were eventually relegated from the top flight. He continued to play a big part as George Burley's team attempted to get back into the top flight. Vaughan scored his first goal on 2 April 1996 against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby]] at home. His last appearance for Town was on 14 May 1997 at home against [[Sheffield United F.C.]] in the [[Football League Championship play-offs#1997|Division 1 playoff]] where Ipswich lost on away goals.\n\n[[Manchester City]] manager [[Frank Clark (footballer)|Frank Clark]] made City fan Vaughan a pre season signing in 1997 for \u00a31.35&nbsp;million. He left for [[Nottingham Forest]] in 1999, where he scored once against [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/1028022.stm\n|title=Nottm Forest 1\u20132 Wimbledon\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> in 43 league games. After loan spells at [[Scunthorpe United]] and [[Mansfield Town]] he moved to Scotland to play for [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] on loan in January 2003.<ref name=\"Well make double swoop\">{{cite web|title=Well make double swoop|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/motherwell/2714685.stm|accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref> At Motherwell he scored one goal against [[Dundee United]] in 12 games.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/2991263.stm\n|title=Nothing between United and Well\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=3 May 2003 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> Vaughan rejoined Mansfield, this time on a permanent basis, in the Summer of 2003, before ending his professional career at [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]], where he also had a loan spell at Stockport County (scoring once against [[Leyton Orient]]).<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/4314964.stm\n|title=Stockport 1\u20131 Leyton Orient\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=8 October 2005 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVaughan resided in [[Nottingham]] after his career came to an end, but now works for AKW Global As A Driver.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vaughan, Tony}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Ipswich Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scunthorpe United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mansfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Motherwell F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stockport County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hucknall Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football utility players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tony Vaughan\n| image = \n| fullname = Anthony John Vaughan<ref>{{Hugman|20124|accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1975|10|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Manchester]], England\n| height =\n| position = [[Defender (football)|Defender]]/[[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1=\n| youthclubs1=\n| years1 = 1994\u20131997 | years2 = 1997\u20132000 | years3 = 1999 | years4 = 2000 | years5 = 2000\u20132003 | years6 = 2002 | years7 = 2002 | years8 = 2003 | years9 = 2003\u20132004 | years10 = 2004\u20132006 | years11 =2005| years12 = 2005\u20132006\n| clubs1 = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] | clubs2 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] (loan) | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] (loan) | clubs5 = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] (loan) | clubs7 = \u2192 [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] (loan) | clubs8 = \u2192 [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] (loan) | clubs9 = [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] | clubs10 = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] | clubs11 = \u2192 [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] (loan) | clubs12 =[[Hucknall Town F.C.|Hucknall Town]]\n| caps1 = 65 | goals1 = 3 | caps2 = 59 | goals2 = 2 | caps3 = 14 | goals3 = 0 | caps4 = 6 | goals4 = 0 | caps5 = 37 | goals5 = 1 | caps6 = 5 | goals6 = 0 | caps7 = 4 | goals7 = 0 | caps8 = 12 | goals8 = 1 | caps9 = 32 | goals9 = 2 | caps10 = 27 | goals10 = 4 | caps11 = 10 | goals11 = 1| caps12 = | goals12 =\n| nationalyears1=\n| nationalteam1=\n| nationalcaps1= | nationalgoals1 =\n| club-update =\n| ntupdate =\n}}\n'''Anthony John Vaughan''' (born 11 October 1975 in [[Manchester]]) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[defender (football)|defender]]/[[midfielder]] from 1994 until 2006.\n\nHe played [[Premier League]] football for [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] before moving into the [[Football League]] with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]], [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]], [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] and [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]]. He also played in the [[Scottish Premier League]] for [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] and finished his career in non-league football with [[Hucknall Town F.C.|Hucknall Town]].\n\n==Playing career==\nVaughan was a product of the [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] youth scheme where he became a trainee.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/manchester_city/article5780357.ece Manchester City save best till last]</ref> He later joined [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich]] as a youth, before making his full debut on 23 October 1994 against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at Stamford Bridge in the [[FA Premier League]]. He started 10 times in that season where Ipswich were eventually relegated from the top flight. He continued to play a big part as George Burley's team attempted to get back into the top flight. Vaughan scored his first goal on 2 April 1996 against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby]] at home. His last appearance for Town was on 14 May 1997 at home against [[Sheffield United F.C.]] in the [[Football League Championship play-offs#1997|Division 1 playoff]] where Ipswich lost on away goals.\n\n[[Manchester City]] manager [[Frank Clark (footballer)|Frank Clark]] made City fan Vaughan a pre season signing in 1997 for \u00a31.35&nbsp;million. He left for [[Nottingham Forest]] in 1999, where he scored once against [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/1028022.stm\n|title=Nottm Forest 1\u20132 Wimbledon\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> in 43 league games. After loan spells at [[Scunthorpe United]] and [[Mansfield Town]] he moved to Scotland to play for [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] on loan in January 2003.<ref name=\"Well make double swoop\">{{cite web|title=Well make double swoop|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/motherwell/2714685.stm|accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref> At Motherwell he scored one goal against [[Dundee United]] in 12 games.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/2991263.stm\n|title=Nothing between United and Well\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=3 May 2003 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> Vaughan rejoined Mansfield, this time on a permanent basis, in the Summer of 2003, before ending his professional career at [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]], where he also had a loan spell at Stockport County (scoring once against [[Leyton Orient]]).<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/4314964.stm\n|title=Stockport 1\u20131 Leyton Orient\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=8 October 2005 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVaughan resided in [[Nottingham]] after his career came to an end, but now works for AKW Global As A Driver.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vaughan, Tony}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Ipswich Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scunthorpe United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mansfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Motherwell F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stockport County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hucknall Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football utility 